        <p class="date">Published: September 10, 2025</p>

        <p>Running a small business comes with unique tax responsibilities and opportunities. By understanding the rules
            and keeping organized records, you can minimize taxes owed and maximize your deductions.</p>

        <h2>1. Track All Expenses</h2>
        <p>Keep detailed records of all business-related expenses including supplies, software, travel, and utilities.
            These
            costs are often fully deductible and can significantly reduce taxable income.</p>

        <h2>2. Take Advantage of Home Office Deduction</h2>
        <p>If you use part of your home exclusively for business, you may be eligible to deduct a portion of rent,
            mortgage
            interest, utilities, and even home insurance.</p>

        <h2>3. Deduct Vehicle Expenses</h2>
        <p>Business-related vehicle use can be deducted using either the standard mileage rate or actual expenses.
            Maintain
            a mileage log to substantiate your deduction.</p>

        <h2>4. Contribute to Retirement Plans</h2>
        <p>Small business owners can set up retirement plans like SEP IRAs, SIMPLE IRAs, or 401(k)s. Contributions are
            deductible and help save for the future.</p>

        <h2>5. Hire a Professional Tax Preparer</h2>
        <p>Small business taxes can be complex. A professional can help identify all eligible deductions, credits, and
            filing strategies to reduce your tax liability.</p>

